<p>As a unit of volume, 1 US cup (half a US pint) is officially 0.24 l; but<br>
a cup of tea or coffee is usually about 0.18 l. To raise 50 cups of water, at<br>
0.18 l per cup, from 15 &deg;C to 100 &deg;C requires 1 kWh.<br></p>
<p>So &ldquo;nine million cups of tea per year&rdquo; is another way of saying &ldquo;20 kW.&rdquo;</p>
<h4>Double-decker buses, Albert Halls and Wembley stadiums</h4>
<p class="first">&ldquo;If everyone in the UK that could, installed cavity wall insulation, we could<br>
cut carbon dioxide emissions by a huge 7 million tons. That&rsquo;s enough<br>
carbon dioxide to fill nearly 40 million double-decker buses or fill the new<br>
Wembley stadium 900 times!&rdquo;<br></p>
<p>From which we learn the helpful fact that one Wembley is 44 000 double<br>
decker buses. Actually, Wembley&rsquo;s bowl has a volume of 1 140 000 m<sup>3</sup>.<br></p>
<p>&ldquo;If every household installed just one energy saving light bulb, there<br>
would be enough carbon dioxide saved to fill the Royal Albert Hall 1,980<br>
times!&rdquo; (An Albert Hall is 100 000 m<sup>3</sup>.)<br></p>
<p>Expressing amounts of CO<sub>2</sub> by volume rather than mass is a great way<br>
to make them sound big. Should &ldquo;1 kg of CO<sub>2</sub> per day&rdquo; sound too small,<br>
just say &ldquo;200 000 litres of CO<sub>2</sub> per year&rdquo;!<br></p>
<h2>More volumes</h2>
<p class="first">A container is 2.4 m wide by 2.6 m high by (6.1 or 12.2) metres long (for<br>
the TEU and FEU respectively).<br></p>
<p>One TEU is the size of a small 20-foot container &ndash; an interior volume<br>
of about 33 m<sup>3</sup>. Most containers you see today are 40-foot containers with<br>
a size of 2 TEU. A 40-foot container weighs 4 tons and can carry 26 tons of<br>
stuff; its volume is 67.5 m<sup>3</sup>.<br></p>
<p>A swimming pool has a volume of about 3000 m<sup>3</sup>.<br></p>
<p>One double decker bus has a volume of 100 m<sup>3</sup>.<br></p>
<p>One hot air balloon is 2500 m<sup>3</sup>.<br></p>
<p>The great pyramid at Giza has a volume of 2 500 000 cubic metres.<br></p>
<h2>Areas</h2>
<p class="first">The area of the earth&rsquo;s surface is 500 &times; 106 km<sup>2</sup>; the land area is 150 &times;<br>
106 km<sup>2</sup>.<br></p>
<p>My typical British 3-bedroom house has a floor area of 88 m<sup>2</sup>. In the<br>
USA, the average size of a single-family house is 2330 square feet (216 m<sup>2</sup>).<br></p>
